---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import NewsletterCallout from '../components/NewsletterCallout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="About" description="About Stern Capital Research, a student-produced educational research publication." noDisclaimer>
  <section class="about-hero"><div class="shell about-hero-grid"><div><span class="eyebrow">About the publication</span><h1>Research is a<br /><em>practice.</em></h1><p>Stern Capital Research is the editorial arm of Stern Capital Management, NYU Stern’s student-run hedge fund club. It gives members a place to develop, challenge, and communicate investment ideas through disciplined research.</p><p>Our aim is not to predict every market move. It is to make the research process visible: forming a question, gathering evidence, testing a thesis, identifying what could go wrong, and communicating conclusions with clarity.</p></div><div class="about-principles"><div class="principle"><span>01</span><h2>Student produced</h2><p>Every publication is authored and reviewed by students learning the craft.</p></div><div class="principle"><span>02</span><h2>Evidence led</h2><p>We value primary sources, explicit assumptions, and falsifiable thinking.</p></div><div class="principle"><span>03</span><h2>Educational by design</h2><p>All portfolios and investment discussions are simulated unless stated otherwise.</p></div></div></div></section>
  <section class="mission-section"><div class="shell mission-grid"><div><span class="eyebrow">Our purpose</span><h2>Learn in public.</h2></div><div><p><strong>Stern Capital Management is a student organization, not an investment adviser or asset manager for outside clients.</strong> This site is a learning environment for members to build analytical judgment, receive editorial feedback, and contribute useful educational materials to the student community.</p><p>Publication does not imply institutional endorsement. The views belong to the individual authors and may evolve as new information emerges. Readers should treat every article as a student exercise—not a solicitation, offer, or recommendation.</p></div></div></section>
  <Disclaimer />
  <section class="section shell"><div class="section-heading"><div><span class="eyebrow">Editorial standards</span><h2>How we publish</h2></div></div><div class="coverage-grid" style="background:var(--navy-950)"><article class="coverage-card"><div><span>01</span><h3>Transparent assumptions</h3><p>We distinguish facts, estimates, scenarios, and author judgments.</p></div></article><article class="coverage-card"><div><span>02</span><h3>Clear sourcing</h3><p>Long-form work is designed to support citations, notes, and primary materials.</p></div></article><article class="coverage-card"><div><span>03</span><h3>Constructive review</h3><p>Editors focus on reasoning, evidence, readability, and intellectual honesty.</p></div></article></div></section>
  <NewsletterCallout />
</BaseLayout>
